<PubmedArticleSet>
<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">30643959</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2019</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>18</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2024</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>01</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1439-6327</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>119</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2019</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>European journal of applied physiology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Eur J Appl Physiol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effects of various interval training regimes on changes in maximal oxygen uptake, body composition, and muscular strength in sedentary women with obesity.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>879</StartPage><EndPage>888</EndPage><MedlinePgn>879-888</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1007/s00421-019-04077-x</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">We determined the effects of two high-intensity interval training (HIIT) regimens [the traditional (TRAD) and periodized (PER)] on changes in maximal oxygen uptake (VO<sub>2</sub>max), body composition, and muscular strength in sedentary, obese women.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Seventeen women (age and BMI&#x2009;=&#x2009;37.5&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;10.5&#xa0;year and 39.1&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;4.3&#xa0;kg/m<sup>2</sup>) were randomized into a 6&#xa0;week regime of TRAD or PER which consisted of three sessions per week, two in the laboratory, and one on their own. Pre- and post-training, VO<sub>2</sub>max, body composition, and muscular strength of the knee extensors (KE) and flexors (KF) were assessed via ramp cycling to exhaustion, air displacement plethysmography, and isokinetic dynamometry, respectively.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">VO<sub>2</sub>max was increased by 4-5% in response to training (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.045) with no group-by-time interaction (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.79). Body mass, fat mass, and waist-to-hip ratio were unaltered (p&#x2009;&gt;&#x2009;0.05) in response to training, yet there was a significant change in percent body fat (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.03), percent fat-free mass (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.03), and absolute fat-free mass (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.03) in TRAD but not PER. No change occurred in KE (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.36) or KF torque (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.75) in response to training and there was no group-by-time interaction (p&#x2009;&gt;&#x2009;0.05).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Low-volume HIIT improved VO<sub>2</sub>max and body composition but did not modify muscular strength, which suggests that obese women desiring to increase strength should initiate more intense HIIT or partake in formal resistance training.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Clark</LastName><ForeName>Amy</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Kinesiology, California State University, 333. S. Twin Oaks Valley Road, UNIV 320, San Marcos, CA, 92096-0001, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>De La Rosa</LastName><ForeName>Annie B</ForeName><Initials>AB</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Kinesiology, California State University, 333. S. Twin Oaks Valley Road, UNIV 320, San Marcos, CA, 92096-0001, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>DeRevere</LastName><ForeName>Jamie L</ForeName><Initials>JL</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Kinesiology, California State University, 333. S. Twin Oaks Valley Road, UNIV 320, San Marcos, CA, 92096-0001, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Astorino</LastName><ForeName>Todd A</ForeName><Initials>TA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affi